WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hi, my name is Vasant Marur. I'm a Senior Data Scientist at Merck.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
For those of you who don't know, it's a big pharma company. We make drugs and vaccines.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.000
I think as all data scientists, we can all agree, if you bring garbage in, you're going to get garbage out.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
And in my field, pharma, the stakes are really high.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So today, I'm going to talk about how we avoid garbage in, garbage out, or GIGO, in your Deep Learning Models.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.000
So, what do we use Deep Learning for?

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Wait, it's not working.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Ah, sorry.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.000
There we go.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
What do we use Deep Learning for?

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Our Deep Learning Models classify images like this.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
These are images of cells, specifically macrophages.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Don't worry about that. I'll get to what macrophages are.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:51.000
So, the images look like this, but sometimes they look like this.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Though they look pretty, these have artifacts in them.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.000
What are artifacts? Artifacts could be debris, could be hair.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Sometimes the liquid dries out, so you don't get a good image.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So, artifacts are a bad thing, even though these images look pretty.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
So, we need quality control to help us flag these images,

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.000
so that we can get really high-quality images of the cells to train our Deep Learning Models,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:20.000
because these images help us find drugs that help cure disease.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Without really good quality images, our Deep Learning Models will spill out garbage.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
So, why are we collecting these images?

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Let me go into what macrophages are.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
So, macrophages are basically a white blood cell, basically an immune cell.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
What's their job? They kill bacteria, dangerous microorganisms.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
They stimulate other immune system cells.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
They start off in a state called M0, and they can go to a state called M1,

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
which is pro-inflammatory, or M2, which is anti-inflammatory.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Now, when the balance is upset, they can cause disease.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And these can range from autoimmune diseases, like MS,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
and including neurodegenerative diseases like Alzheimer's.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And if they go the other way, to M2, they can cause cancer.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.000
So, we want to find a way to control these macrophages,

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
because if we can try to modulate these macrophages,

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
then we might be able to help cure disease.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
So, on the left, on the top, you can see some images of examples

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
of the different kind of cells we have.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
These are M1, M0, and M2.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
But how do we take these images?

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So, we use a microscope, but you can't just use a microscope.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
You need to take some really good pictures.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
So, first, we start off with this technique called cell painting.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
That's literally, as you might think, we take different colored dyes,

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
and we color different parts of the cell with different dyes,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
and then take images in different channels.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And so, that lets you see every single part of the cell,

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
as you can see on the bottom.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
So, you can get a good, complete picture.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And why are we doing this?

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Well, the idea is that cell morphology,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
which is a fancy name for the shape, the size, the texture of the cell,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
and if you can look at the image,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.000
you can see what's happening to these cells.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
So, by taking these images and then training a deep learning model,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
we hope to classify them and find different classes.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
So, in effect, we're searching for new drugs that alleviate disease

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.000
by using a technique called high-throughput screening and imaging.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
What's high-throughput screening?

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
It's basically a very easy, well, not very easy, very rapid way

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
to test a lot of compounds against a biological target.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
So, you can test a lot of these compounds, like thousands of them, very rapidly.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
And we do that with imaging.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
So, this is a busy slide, but I want to help you, walk you through it.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
So, we start with some cells.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
We get them from disease patients and normal patients,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
and then we add compounds to them,

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
or we change the genome a little bit using a technique called CRISPR,

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
and then we do high-throughput screening and imaging.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Once we have these images, you can get lots of features from them,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
and then do groupings and clusterings.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
So, as part of the drug discovery effort,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
we use both the high-throughput screening and imaging to help us get these images.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Now, in practice, this is what our pipeline looks like, or where I work.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
So, once we get the images from the scientists,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
and we get some metadata about what these images are,

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
we do something called ImageQC, where we look for artifacts,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
or we look for images that are not good,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
and then we follow up with image segmentation,

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
where we try to find every single cell in an image,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
and we try to find the coordinates.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Once we have that information, we train a deep learning model,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
and then we can do further downstream analysis.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
So, this whole pipeline is built in NextFlow,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.000
that's a workflow manager, and deployed in AWS.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But today, I'm mainly going to focus on the ImageQC part,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
because that's how you can avoid Geico,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
because you don't want garbage in deep learning models,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.000
because you don't want to get garbage out.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
So, our scientists are doing a lot of images.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
You know, they look like this, this, and this.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So, you get the picture, a lot of images.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
How many images?

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Well, an experiment could have, what, 40,000 images on the low end,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
to about more than 200,000 images.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
So, I talked about QC.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Now, imagine going through and checking every single image manually.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
That's tedious.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
It's going to be time-consuming.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
It's basically impossible.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
So, how do we do ImageQC?

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
Well, we decided we should automate it.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And how do we do that?

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Well, enter Python.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
I know this is more R, but no, I'll get to that.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So, we had a team that had already written a tool using Python to do ImageQC.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So, once we get the images, we use this in-house tool.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
It computes a bunch of image metrics for us

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
and then uses a technique called isolation forest to find outliers and inliers,

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.000
in effect, giving us a list of good and bad images.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
So, the whole process looks like this.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Once we get the images, we compute the image metrics.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Then, we take the isolation forest model,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
feed them these metrics as features,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
and in an isolation forest, you can give an automatic threshold

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
or you can specify a threshold if you don't know.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
So, that will take that threshold

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
and then show you the list of good and bad images for us.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
So, this is another busy slide.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Don't worry about it.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
We basically compute a lot of these image metrics.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
So, basically from the computer vision field.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
But once we have these, we feed them to the isolation forest

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
and then that uses these metrics as features

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
to do further processing.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
So, what does isolation forest do, really?

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
So, once we have those image metrics, as I showed you,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
it calculates a score.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
It ranges from minus one to zero.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Once it has the score, and then it uses a threshold,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
so automatic, as I mentioned,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
and then it finds the outliers and inliers.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Now, you can specify a threshold if you think,

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.000
oh, maybe 3% of my images are bad or 4%.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:19.000
But you see where I'm going with this.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
It's kind of arbitrary.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
If you give it a high percentage,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:27.000
you might lose a lot of images, which are actually good,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
but you're rejecting all these good images

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:30.000
that you've collected.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
So, you want to adjust that threshold.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Well, how do we do that?

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Well, we just run the Python tool again, right?

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
But we're dealing with non-computational scientists.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
Telling them to run a Python tool, that's basically hard,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
especially when they were students in the command line.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
They end up like the IKEA guy.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
You know, we give them all the instructions,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
but they always end up having issues.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:58.000
So, how do we help them?

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
Because having a computational tool is not enough

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:02.000
if people can't use it.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
It has to be easy for them to use.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
So, I was thinking, hey, we could pre-compute these metrics

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
using the Python tool,

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
and then it would be really cool

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
if we could give them a way for them to adjust the threshold,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
see which images are getting flagged,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.000
see which images are not good,

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:22.000
and then keep adjusting it

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
until they're satisfied with the output of the QC.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And then once we have that, then they can go forward.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:30.000
So, oh, wait, there's something called Shiny.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:31.000
We can do that.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
So, that's where we use Shiny.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.000
So, we have a tool like this.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
The interface looks like that.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
On the top, they can adjust the cutoff.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
And let me just walk you through what the interface looks like.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
It gives you a list of bad images on the top,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:48.000
good images in the middle,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
and the best quality images on the board.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.000
And as they adjust it,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.000
so this is starting off with the automatic threshold,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
and you can see there are some images on the top

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
where there are like some images of cells,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
some images have nothing in them.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So, you do want to catch those.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
You can adjust the threshold,

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
and then you can see you get more images which are not great.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So, you can keep doing this until they're happy.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
And as you adjust the threshold,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
you get, it regenerates which images are getting flagged,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
which images are not great, and so on.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
So, in this way, we can give them a tool.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
They could adjust threshold,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
and they can see which images are getting flagged,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
which images are not great.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And once you're satisfied,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
they generate a set of good images.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
So, by the way, this is all deployed on, you know,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
using Connect and deployed on AWS.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
So, this allowed us to generate, give them a lot of data,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
but still the app worked great.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
So, thanks to Connect.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
So, just to give you an idea

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
of how many images are getting flagged.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.000
So, on a plate, we get about 3,000 odd images.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
So, if you choose the automatic threshold,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.000
you can reject up to 10% of these images,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
which is really not great

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
because you might be losing a few images

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
that are actually good.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
So, we can keep adjusting that threshold,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
and then you can see the number of images

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
that are getting flagged reduce.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
So, that's why we decided

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
we should have an interactive web-based version

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
so the imaging scientists could use

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
and be the human in the loop, so to speak,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
and check the quality of the image that you see

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
because without doing that,

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:28.000
they're not going to be satisfied

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
with what our tool is doing.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
So, once we have these images,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
now we can do deep learning.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
So, on the left is an example of a 384-well plate.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
It's basically in which we put all the samples in,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
and what we do to train our deep learning models

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
is we take images from the first two columns

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
and the last two columns.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Now, this is what I call controlled regions

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
on a plate in a biological experiment.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
Controls are basically we already know what they have,

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
so these are labeled data for our deep learning models.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Now, as you can see in the middle,

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
these are the images that come out of those wells,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and you can see there are some that have artifacts in them,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
so then we use our QC tool.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:15.000
It marks those images and flags them as it should.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So, once that's done, we get rid of those images

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
from our deep learning model, and then we train it,

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
and the main goal of doing this is we want to make sure

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
that the deep learning model is using

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
really high-quality images,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:30.000
images that have actual biology or changes happening in them,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
and not have artifacts in them because, again,

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
if they have artifacts, you can't trust the results

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
coming out of these high-quality models.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
So, we basically use deep learning models

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
to get the features from these images

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
and then train a model to know the difference

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
between the different images

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
and then give us a prediction for each well

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
in the sampled region, which is all the yellow in the middle.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
So, on the left and the right are the controls,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
like M0, M1, and M2,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
and in the middle are sample wells,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
which we don't know what's going on,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
but we add compounds to it and perturb them,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
and then we try to see whether it mimics the controls

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.000
on the left or the right,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
and that way we generate a prediction

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
from our deep learning models.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.000
So, to recap, combining the existing Python code

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
that was written already

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
and then using a Shiny-based app for thresholding

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
enables us to get really high-quality images

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
between our deep learning models.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So, this is the way we did it.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
We already had a different team working on image analysis,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
so they developed this Python tool for us.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
So, like, do we need to rewrite this in R?

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Do we need to redo it all?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
No, we can just take that.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
Then we developed the Shiny tool

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
to take the input from the Python tool

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.000
and then give an interface to our imaging scientists

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:52.000
so that they could use this,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
and, you know, everybody's happy this way.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
So, without rewriting or reinventing anything

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:58.000
or rewriting anything,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
we could use the tools that was already written.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.000
So, in this manner,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
we could actually get a really good deep learning model

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
so that we could trust images coming out of it.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
So, of course, this is not possible just with me.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
This is a huge team that worked on it.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
I'm part of the data science team,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
and we collaborate with the image analytics team,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
and there's the biological team for the Mac Pro team,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
and, of course, without IT, you can't get anything done.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:24.000
Huge shout-out to them.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
And then, of course, all the imaging scientists

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
who helped us curate the tool, use it,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
and give us feedback.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
So, with that, thank you.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:44.000
Thank you.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
So, I'm giving you a moment to take a sip of water.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Yeah, thank you.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
I was wondering how long it took you to realize

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
that you needed a shiny app

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
and how long it took you to make that.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
So, it started off with someone actually doing

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
a Python Jupyter notebook,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:05.000
and they were like,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
no, let's just do a Jupyter notebook

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
and give that to the scientists.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
I'm like, no.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
So, I personally am not a fan of notebooks.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:13.000
I hate notebooks.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Oh, I said that too loudly.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.000
Sorry.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
You know, you have notebooks in different cells,

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
and then you're expecting a non-data scientist to go,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
oh, run this cell, then run this cell,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:23.000
then run this cell,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
and then give us an output.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
It would never work.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.000
So, we tried that a few times,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:29.000
and then we said, you know what?

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
I think I can do this in Shiny,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
and we have Workbench.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
We can include the Python code,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:36.000
set up the environment,

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
and just do a Shiny.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
So, a few weeks,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
and then two more weeks

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
as we start up the app very quickly,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:44.000
the first version.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
But we redeveloped this app

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
with more features out.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
So, I would say a long answer

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
for that earlier question,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:53.000
about two months,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
but a lot of feedback.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.000
Nice.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Yeah.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:00.000
Okay.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
So, we got some questions coming.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
This is sort of getting ahead of the session,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
but it keeps in theme with the conference.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So, would a similar approach work in R?

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.000
Yes, it would.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So, for those not familiar,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
I kind of skipped over, I realized.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
So, we use scikit-learn in Python,

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
and Python already has a lot of image utilities

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.000
and image packages

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.000
that make it really easy to develop.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
So, those don't exist in R yet, unfortunately,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
but it works in Python.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:34.000
So, just use that.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:35.000
We use what's available.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
I'm a major fan of using what's available,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
not reinventing the wheel.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
So, can I do this in R completely?

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
No, not completely.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Yep.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
Continuing with the theme of, would this also?

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Yeah.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
So, why not just train the deep learners

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
to find the artifacts?

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
So, this is biology.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:58.000
Nothing works,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
and biology trumps math and data science.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Things keep changing.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:07.000
So, when we first started these series of experiments,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
there's something called batch effects.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So, when you have an experiment today,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
and you do it a month later,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
and you try to use a deep learning model to classify it,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:17.000
it's not going to work.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
We realized, because someone changed something

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
in your experiment, or something happened,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
or again, the batch effects,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
something went wrong in liquid hand,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
something went wrong with the assay,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
or how many cells you used.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
So, we didn't have enough data

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
to just use deep learning straight off,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.000
and we tried it.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:35.000
It would work sometimes.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
It would miss a lot of things.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
So, that's a work in progress.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:40.000
So, once you have more data,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
then I can just ignore this

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
and go back to using deep learning.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:50.000
You definitely got people engaged on your problem here.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
There's more questions about potential solutions.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:55.000
I'm not entirely sure about this one,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
but were ROC curves considered

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
for defining potential thresholds?

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:06.000
ROC curves were applied for thresholds.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
I don't think I quite get that question.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
Maybe they can clarify what they mean.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.000
How would I use that?

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
So, yeah.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:14.000
Right.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
Maybe somebody can put an update.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
So, it was also like,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.000
I'm not sure where this is going,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.000
but okay, maybe we're both on this team.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Yes.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
But please keep them coming.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.000
Oh, this is a different one.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
So, what scale is the back end

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
of the Shiny tool on AWS?

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.000
Like cost and compute volume.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.000
So, hard facts.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
So, cost.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Fortunately, I don't have to worry about that.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
IT takes care of it.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
It's amazing when you work for a big pharma.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
I mean, but I do think about that.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.000
So, it doesn't cost that much.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:56.000
We can do a very cheap spot instances

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
or EC2 instances to get that.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.000
Volume.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
So, that was just one experiment.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
So, the plate that I was talking about,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.000
we collect about 13,000 images.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.000
That's one plate.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
If an experiment has eight plates, multiply that.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
And over the past two years,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:15.000
we've done about 50, 60 odd experiments

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:16.000
with varying plates.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
So, a lot of data.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:19.000
A lot.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.000
So, yeah.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
I love this interaction with you via my phone, oddly,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
but we do have an update on a question.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.000
Okay.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
So, that's at least how I read this new contribution here.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:30.000
It says,

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
I wonder if use of different thresholds

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
would affect the model training.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.000
Yeah.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
So, seriously speaking,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
deep learning is robust enough

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
to handle those kinds of images I showed you.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
It can still be like, oh, it doesn't matter.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.000
But our goal was to have really trustworthy results

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
coming out of these deep learning models

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
because the biologists in the room,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
they want to know that,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:54.000
is it just artifact?

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:55.000
Is it noise?

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Is it just magic?

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.000
No, no.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
It's actually learning from your data.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
So, that's one of the reasons why.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:02.000
We did train some.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
It'll still work,

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
but you can't be sure what it's learning from.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:07.000
So, in this way,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
we can be sure that we are not learning

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
from noise or artifacts in your data.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
It's learning from actual biology.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:14.000
So.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:15.000
Okay.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.000
That's a good question,

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
and we got like 30 seconds.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.000
I'm happy to take that offline.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
I'm here all day and tomorrow.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
We're going to close with this good example

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
of a collaboration between a data scientist

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:37.000
and a subject matter expert.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:38.000
Yep, thank you.

